snippet.textDisplay:
ok hear me out, the player is one of the multiple experiments of the illagers. the player somehow escapes and passes out in a random place without anyone.

the case of the players amnesia at spawn is probably due to their recent creation or they were severely injured.
maybe when notch saw potential in the player they decided to let this creature that the illagers made to become the savoir for others.
that’s why you get guides in the game and achievements leading up to the defeat in the ender dragon. notch is essentially guiding you down the right path.
whenever you’re outside and run into a couple of illagers is because they’re looking for you and the other experiments that escaped the woodland mansions
i’m also going to reference something i saw in the comments, and i’m going to add some of my theory to it. someone pointed out that some limbs on the ravager were similar to the iron golem, maybe the ravagers were a mix of iron golems and villagers. this could also count as an unspeakable actions they did to get kicked out of the villages.
this can be confirmed by the fact that sometimes you’ll find an iron golem in a small jail/prison to used to make more ravagers.
to also people referencing herobrine,
i don’t know much about the creators making herobrine cannon or something if herobrine really does exist then maybe we can speculate that herobrine was a successful experiment if they wanted a creature who could never die/with unlimited power.

please forgive me if what i’m saying makes absolutely no sense, or what i’m saying is incorrect. my minecraft knowledge isn’t that great but it’s what i pieced together from this one video

snippet.textDisplay:
Villagers can't do what the player (or Steve) can do (namely: mine, tho' they can craft, well, kinda), so, they're really jealous of the player character... I think that envy was what turned them into the illagers... They're not really evil, they just want to be at least as powerful, if not more, than the player... if you think about it: there's only one "human" (Steve), might as well be the last human alive as far as we know... but... this human isn't an ordinary person, this human, to the villagers, is basically a near-omnipotent, god-like entity, that does as he pleases (I'd turn into an illager if I saw a so called "villager farm" - kidnapping, slavery, breeding, murder,...)... Steve is the real "villain" in this story! (and if there was a game theory about this or similar, oops, but I haven't seen it)

also: the ravager is big, maybe it's made from more than just one villager (IF they really are made out of villagers, that is), even tho' Minecraft's "laws of physics" are different than the real world's, and it doesn't care much about the conservation of mass

snippet.textDisplay: I have a question about the phantoms and elytra (not directly related to this vid but I was hoping that my question might be answered in a following video fo this amazing series): The elytra are probably made from phantom membrane, since that's what you repair them with. And yet phantoms only appear when you don't sleep IN THE OVERWORLD. Now here's the thing: the builders obviously didn't make any elytra in the overworld, as you can't find them anywhere besides the end city ships. And they didn't know what they were going into when they went into the end, and so they wouldn't know that elytra would be really useful in the end dimension. So how were the elytra made? Are phantoms originally from the end? If so, how did they become things that only appear as a cause of insomnia in the overworld exclusively? I don't know, maybe this is just me looking for inconsistencies. But if you want to see this question answered, please like so the game theorists can see, cuz this is really bugging me and I'm not knowledgeable enough about minecraft stuff to answer this question.

snippet.textDisplay: What im about to explain, stands true for most things similar in nature. I personally think that the reason we may find the theories based on the lore somtimes more dramatic and or terrifying is because we were only theorizing. The pinch of uncertainty which makes you question whether such an assumption could reign true is what makes it scarier. Thinking that perhaps not since it cant be that dark right? Then battling with yourself whether you are just going to far or if you really are on to somthing more sinister.... it's a creepy thing to think about. A good way to look at it is to imagine having these theories actually being explicitly put into the game in the sense that we always knew that's what it was. It would seem more normal and since we aren't theorizing about if it's possible, anx in turn, the fear factor of such a thing seems to diminish. Now of course, there is some psychological explanation for this but I most definitely thought it was rather interesting. I could write more, but I'll leave it at that for now.
